f=Shared OS/logical/mckee-story-structure.md · in=Robert McKee's *Story* (1997) definitive treatise narrative design. McKee argues story genre-dependent formula set universal principles govern human beings experience meaning. His central thesis: **"Story about principles, rules. rule says, 'You way.' principle says, 'This works ... through remembered time.'"** (Introduction, p.3) extraction bridges McKee's screenwriting architecture narrative frameworks Brand Studio brand story, campaign narrative, content arc pass through McKee's structural gate before production. · h2:PART 5-PART DRAMATIC STRUCTURE=*Ch.8-13, pp.163-307* McKee's famous structural contribution five-part dramatic spine, which maps onto classic three-act structure provides richer detail. · h3:2.1 The Inciting Incident=*Ch.8, pp.163-185* "The Inciting Incident radically upsets balance forces protagonist's life." (Ch.8, p.169) Inciting Incident must: **Happen protagonist** passively observed. McKee (Ch.8, p.172): "The protagonist react Inciting Incident." **Radically upset balance** world BEFORE incident equilibrium. After, not. Irreversibly. **Raise Major Dramatic Question** question audience hold until climax. protagonist achieve their desire? **Occur right moment** McKee (Ch.8, p.178): "Bring Central Plot's Inciting Incident soon possible ... until moment ripe." early: audience doesn't care. late: audience bored. **Brand application:** Inciting Incident brand narrative problem disrupts customer's equilibrium. Before: everything fine (stasis). After: problem emerges (inciting incident). product guide helps protagonist navigate disrupted world. · h3:2.2 Progressive Complications=*Ch.9, pp.186-207* "The second element five-part design Progressive Complications: series events makes protagonist's pursuit desire increasingly difficult." (Ch.9, p.189) McKee's key insight: **complications progress difficulty depth.** complication harder last. antagonist's forces intensify. stakes rise. **The Gap Principle (Ch.7, pp.145-160):** "The Gap difference between expectation result. protagonist takes action, expecting particular result. result something else entirely opening gap between what expected what happened. protagonist's next action bridge gap." McKee (Ch.7, p.150): "Story born Gap." Gap drama lives. scene without Gap protagonist acts gets exactly expected result scene; it's exposition. turning point narrative Gap: protagonist's expectation violated, forcing adaptation. **Brand application:** Gap principle mechanism demonstrating product value. Before: customer expects solution work. Gap: fails, creates new problem. Bridge: your product/service. bigger gap between expectation result, dramatic memorable brand story. · h3:2.3 Crisis=*Ch.13, pp.278-290* "The Crisis story's Obligatory Scene. moment greatest tension, protagonist faces powerful forces antagonism make decision which turning back." (Ch.13, p.280) McKee distinguishes Crisis Climax: · h3:2.3 Crisis=**Crisis DECISION.** protagonist stands crossroads two (or more) irreconcilable goods, lesser two evils, chosen. McKee (Ch.13, p.283): "True choice dilemma.", **Climax ACTION flows decision.** · h3:2.3 Crisis=Crisis "obligatory scene" scene audience waiting since Inciting Incident. promise story made audience beginning. **Brand application:** Crisis brand narrative moment customer choose between old way (failing, painful, inadequate) new way (your solution). genuine dilemma real cost change vs. cost staying powerful narrative. · h3:2.4 Climax=*Ch.13, pp.291-300* "The Climax story's ultimate reversal. Crisis decision, protagonist acts world irrevocably changed." (Ch.13, p.292) McKee's rules Climax: **It answer Major Dramatic Question.** McKee (Ch.13, p.294): "All story telling promise. Inciting Incident raises Major Dramatic Question; Climax answers it." **It absolute climax.** scene carry emotional weight. Climax happens page pages, structure broken. **It produce Value Change.** story began certain charge value (e.g., negative: injustice). climax reverses charge (positive: justice) negates utterly (the negation negation: injustice triumphant). · h3:2.5 Resolution=*Ch.13, pp.301-307* "The Resolution, fifth element five-part structure, aftermath Climax. closes story's open threads shows new equilibrium." (Ch.13, p.303) Resolution serves three purposes: **Show new balance** world after climax different. resolution establishes new normal. **Close subplots** secondary character arcs resolved. **Provide emotional closure** audience needs moment process climax's impact. McKee warns (Ch.13, p.305): "The Resolution brief. longer resolution, audience's emotional experience climax dissipates. resolution goes long author who can't let go." **Brand application:** Resolution brand narrative "after" picture customer using product, life improved, new normal established. Testimonials, case studies, product demos structural Resolutions. · h2:PART GAP PRINCIPLE (Extended)=*Ch.7, pp.145-162* McKee's Gap Principle engine dramatic action, maps directly onto brand storytelling challenge. **McKee's model (Ch.7, pp.148-155):** Protagonist **Desire** (conscious want). Protagonist takes **Action** achieve desire. world **reacts** reaction what protagonist expected. **Gap** opens between expectation result. protagonist choose **new action** bridge gap. **Repeat** cycle escalates stakes, deepens character, surprises audience. **The Gap brand storytelling:** · h2:PART GAP PRINCIPLE (Extended)=Customer's expectation: "The generic/competitor/DIY solution work.", Gap: "It didn't work. created new problem. adequate transformative.", Bridge: Your product/service closes gap way customer couldn't predicted., New expectation: Life better your solution., New gap (for ongoing narrative): Even your solution, new challenges emerge your brand evolves. · h2:PART GAP PRINCIPLE (Extended)=**Connection Berger (STEPPS Stories, Ch.6):** "The Gap people tell stories. everything goes expected, story. Gap story." · h3:The 5-Part Structure Validator=brand narrative, check 5-part structure: · h3:The 5-Part Structure Validator=\| # \| Element \| Check \| · h3:The 5-Part Structure Validator=\|---\|---------\|-------\| · h3:The 5-Part Structure Validator=\| 1 \| **Inciting Incident** \| Is there a clear moment that disrupts the protagonist's equilibrium? \| · h3:The 5-Part Structure Validator=\| 2 \| **Progressive Complications** \| Do obstacles escalate in difficulty? Does each complication raise stakes? \| · h3:The 5-Part Structure Validator=\| 3 \| **Crisis** \| Is there a genuine dilemma — a choice between two irreconcilable goods or lesser evils? \| · h3:The 5-Part Structure Validator=\| 4 \| **Climax** \| Does the climactic action answer the Major Dramatic Question? Is it the peak of emotional intensity? \| · h3:The 5-Part Structure Validator=\| 5 \| **Resolution** \| Is the new equilibrium shown? Is the audience given emotional closure? \| · h3:The Scene Value-Change Detector=scene (video segment, beat, content block), check: · h3:The Scene Value-Change Detector=**Opening value charge:** start unit, value stake positive (+) negative (-)?, **Closing value charge:** end, flipped?, **If flip:** scene it's exposition. Cut restructure it. · h3:The Gap Detector=For every turning point: · h3:The Gap Detector=What protagonist's expected result?, What actually happened?, meaningful gap between them?, gap force new, difficult choice? · h3:The Character-Desire-Antagonism Triangle=For every brand narrative: · h3:The Character-Desire-Antagonism Triangle=**Protagonist:** customer. brand., **Conscious Desire:** What customer WANTS (the surface problem)., **Unconscious Desire:** What customer NEEDS (the deeper truth)., **Antagonism:** competitor. true opponent internal limit, false solution, systemic problem., **Guide:** brand. brand helps protagonist bridge gap replace protagonist. · h2:BOUNDARIES WITH OTHER SCRIPTS=**storyline_engine.py:** Implements 5-part structure validator, Gap detector, Character-Desire-Antagonism triangle checker, scene value-change detector, tension curve estimator extraction., **heath-made-to-stick.md:** Heath's Stories principle (Ch.6) "why" storytelling; McKee provides "how." SUCCESs scores narrative effectiveness; McKee diagnoses narrative structure., **berger-contagious.md:** Berger's Stories Trojan Horse maps onto McKee's Controlling Idea horse (story structure) carry soldiers (brand message) without about soldiers., **marketing_laws.py:** Campbell's Hero's Journey (law_hero_journey placeholder) archetypal pattern underlying McKee's structural principles.